    97	### D.3 Auth flow — HTTP Basic via per-experiment credential helper
    98	
    99	The reference Gitea is exposed on plain HTTP inside the compose
   100	network (no TLS). That matches the existing soft-isolation
   101	posture documented in §7 of
   102	[`spec/v0/reference-bindings/worker-host-subprocess.md`](../../spec/v0/reference-bindings/worker-host-subprocess.md):
   103	the reference deployment trades isolation for operational
   104	simplicity. A hardened deployment terminates TLS at a sidecar or
   105	Gitea-side reverse proxy, swapping the `http://gitea:3000/...`
   106	URL for `https://gitea/...`; the workers' `--gitea-url` flag is
   107	opaque to the rest of the design. We document this caveat
   108	alongside the existing DooD soft boundary; the secret-handling
   109	boundary widens by exactly one channel (now the eden user's
   110	Gitea password is also visible to anyone with daemon access).
   111	
   112	setup-experiment.sh, after starting Gitea + waiting for healthy:
   113	
   114	1. Generate a per-experiment password `GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD`
   115	   (32 hex bytes; same shape as other reference secrets).
   116	2. Provision the eden user (idempotent — first checks via
   117	   `gitea admin user list`):
   118	
   119	   ```bash
   120	   docker compose exec -T gitea gitea admin user create \
   121	       --username eden \
   122	       --password "${GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD}" \
   123	       --email eden@invalid \
   124	       --admin
   125	   ```
   126	
   127	   Re-running with a different password updates the existing
   128	   user (`gitea admin user change-password`) so re-runs of
   129	   setup-experiment with new env files don't desync.
   130	3. Generate a per-experiment access token (used only by
   131	   setup-experiment for repo creation, NOT by workers; workers
   132	   use Basic auth):
   133	
   134	   ```bash
   135	   curl -fsS -u "eden:${GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD}" \
   136	       -X POST http://localhost:${GITEA_HOST_PORT}/api/v1/users/eden/tokens \
   137	       -d '{"name":"setup","scopes":["write:repository"]}'
   138	   ```
   139	
   140	4. Create the repo `eden/<EXPERIMENT_ID>.git` via
   141	   `POST /api/v1/user/repos` (idempotent — handle 409).
   142	5. Write the **credential-helper script** to a host-side path
   143	   `${COMPOSE_DIR}/.gitea-creds-${EXPERIMENT_ID}/credential-helper.sh`,
   144	   substituting the password into a template. The script:
   145	
   146	   ```sh
   147	   #!/bin/sh
   148	   case "$1" in
   149	     get)
   150	       cat <<EOF
   151	   username=eden
   152	   password=__GITEA_REMOTE_PASSWORD__
   153	   EOF
   154	       ;;
   155	   esac
   156	   ```
   157	
   158	   Mode 0755. Mounted read-only into every worker host container
   159	   at `/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh`.
   160	
   161	Workers configure git to use the helper via repo-local config
   162	written at clone time (NOT global config — keeps the secret out
   163	of the worker's home dir):
   164	
   165	```bash
   166	git -c credential.helper="/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh" \
   167	    -c http.extraHeader="" \
   168	    clone http://gitea:3000/eden/<EXPERIMENT_ID>.git \
   169	    /var/lib/eden/repo
   170	git -C /var/lib/eden/repo config credential.helper \
   171	    "/etc/eden/credential-helper.sh"
   172	```
   173	
   174	Subsequent `git fetch` / `git push` invocations from that repo
   175	pick up the helper automatically. The chunk-10d-followup-A
   176	soft-boundary caveat (§7) is extended to cover this: the eden
   177	user's Gitea password is on the host filesystem at
   178	`${COMPOSE_DIR}/.gitea-creds-<id>/credential-helper.sh` mode 0755,
   179	readable by anyone on the host and (under DooD) by any
   180	concurrent `*_command`.
